ard.com/utuamigo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tuamigo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/5/02 6:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=100.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Breaking it down</span><hr size=1> Ok, apparently my other question over at &quot;past and future&quot; was too broad. Let me break it down a little bit over here to see if I can learn something.<br>
<br>
It seems to me one big difficulty here is the shielding of the passengers from shock waves and radiation.<br>
What is the leading solution about that so far?<br>
Is there a possibility for a controlled reaction, with an effectively smooth throttle, or does it have to be &quot;bang, bang, bang&quot;? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 199<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/6/02 3:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=100.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Breaking it down</span><hr size=1> There have been many proposals for nuclear space propulsion. Our <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.net/nuclear_links.htm">links</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.net/gallery.htm">multimedia gallery</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> can provide a good starting point. The amazing <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com"> Encyclopedia Astronautica </a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->is an excellent resource and has extensive information on many of these systems. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.islandone.org/Propulsion/ProjectOrion.html">Orion</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> was the one that went bang-bang and, in fact, one of its nicknames is &quot;old bang-bang&quot;. Protecting the ship and its occupants from the propulsive shock was a major design consideration, but the designers were convinced that they had found a workable solution. This involved mounting giant shock absorbers on top of the heavy aft (&quot;pusher&quot;) plate, and attaching the rest of the ship to those. The pusher plate itself was the primary defense against radiation. <br>
<br>
Other systems, like <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://spaceflight.nasa.gov/mars/technology/propulsion/aspl/vasimr.html">VASIMIR</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and  <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.net/images/gallery/nerva_63.jpg">NERVA</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> essentially use nuclear energy to heat a working fluid, then expel it to produce thrust, much the same as a familiar chemical rocket. There are many, many variations on this; for example, nuclear-electric propulsion (NEP) uses a nuclear power source for an ion rocket. In these systems, the application of thrust is smooth, as in a chemical rocket, and no unusual shock precautions are necessary. Radiation shielding must be installed around the energy source, as with any closed nuclear system.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A> at: 8/6/02 3:10:53 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utuamigo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tuamigo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/6/02 6:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=100.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Breaking it down</span><hr size=1> Thank you!<br>
You know, I noticed there are all those links and books, articles and info. But one can read that stuff for hours on end before getting the feeling of where we're at. That's why I was hoping for a little shortcut asking for a brief summary in the boards.<br>
Your post sounds like good news. The thing is, what is being done about it? what model is winning favor? when is it going to happen?<br>
<br>
Could I ask for a brief comparison between the candidates? which is the cheapest? which is the fastest? which is the hardest to build? which is the easiest to build? stuff like that. Anybody? Could a small, two person prototype be built now?Come on, bring me up to date please. I promise to keep reading the articles. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 109<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/6/02 10:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=100.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Breaking it down</span><hr size=1> Sorry Atomic Conspiritor, your slightly wrong. VASMIR is a NEP, not a NPR. It's basically one of two types of NEP, the other being the nuclear ion drive, which should be simple enough. Other than that your pretty much right on.<br>
<br>
Let me explain the pusher plate idea a bit more. The plate neets to weigh alot in order to protect itself and the ship from the nuclear blast. Sheer weight is the best protection against radiation.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 44<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/7/02 7:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=100.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Breaking it down</span><hr size=1> brp-I'm gonna hafta disagree with you a bit.<br>
<br>
Sheer weight is usually a decent indicator of atomic density, so for that I'll give you that a shield that is high in mass is usually pretty dense and will thus stop a good amount of gamma and x-ray radiation, as well as alpha and beta of course.  However, keep in mind that what you're going for is density, not weight.  A 1 inch thick plate of stainless steel is an amazing shield, though it may weigh less than a 6-ft thick concrete wall <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
One thing you're forgetting, however, is that there are neutrons being given off too.  Commercial reactors have neutron reflectors, materials to slow down neutrons so that they all become thermal neutrons, and then thermal neutron absorbers.  All of these things must be put in place in addition to what people normally think of for &quot;shielding&quot;.<br>
<br>
As a final note, water itself is an amazing radiation shield <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Not often thought about...but stand 35 feet above a spent fuel pool, with ~28-30 feet of water being the only thing between you and 200 assemblies that give off contact readings of thousands of Rems/hr, and you'll start to notice that the field you're in is maybe .3 mR/hr.   That's some serious shielding <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 110<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/7/02 9:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=100.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Breaking it down</span><hr size=1> Okay, that's true, but the pusher plate would be made of suitably dense materials that it doesn't matter. Concrete, well, that'd be more likely to shatter. Aluminum, steel, titanium, or other space age materials would be much better. Part of the problem with concrete is it's at least somewhat porous, more than steel or whatever other material. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 691<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/7/02 10:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=100.topic&index=6>Reply</a>  