d by the mass of a single ion<br>
 in kilograms multiplied by two times the net accelerating<br>
voltage of the electric field in which the ion is accelerated.<br>
If multiple electric fields are used in a linear ion accelerator<br>
the ion exchaust velocity is equal to the sum of the velocity<br>
increments from all the  electric fields that are used.<br>
If the ion exchaust beam is accelerated through the same electric field multiple times as occurrs in cyclotrons, and synchrotons, the ion exchaust velocity is the cumulative <br>
velocity from all the times the ion beam passed through the same electric field. An ion engine can potentially generate any exchaust velocity up to almost the the velocity of light in actual fact.But the higher the ion  exchaust velocity the more electric power is required for accelerating a given ion beam mass.For example:  It takes 10,000 times more electric power<br>
